Patient Name: Arthur Pendelton
Date: 2026-03-01
Time: 14:30

Chief Complaint: Sudden onset of shortness of breath and sharp chest pain.

History of Present Illness (HPI): The patient is a 62-year-old male who presents to the emergency department reporting acute dyspnea that began approximately 4 hours ago while watching television. He describes a sharp, stabbing pain in the right side of his chest that severely worsens upon taking a deep breath. He denies any recent physical trauma, productive cough, or prior history of cardiac issues. However, he notes that he recently returned from a 14-hour international flight two days ago.

Vitals Recorded:

Temperature: 99 F

Heart Rate: 118 BPM

O2 Saturation: 87 %

Blood Pressure: 135/85 mmHg

Respiratory Rate: 26 breaths/min

Physical Examination: The patient appears visibly anxious and is in mild respiratory distress, utilizing accessory muscles to breathe. Lungs are clear to auscultation bilaterally; no wheezes, rhonchi, or crackles detected. Cardiovascular exam reveals marked tachycardia but a regular rhythm. Examination of the extremities reveals the right calf is mildly swollen, erythematous, and warm to the touch compared to the left leg.

Plan / Next Steps:
Initiate supplemental oxygen via nasal cannula to target O2 > 94%. Order STAT D-Dimer test, bilateral lower extremity venous ultrasound, and prepare for immediate CT imaging of the chest with IV contrast.